If the population is classified into $\mathbf{S}$ , $\mathbf{E}$ , $\mathbf{I}$ and $\mathbf{R}$ compartments such that  egin{equation} \label{eq4}  egin{aligned} \mathbf{S} &=\dfrac{S_{1}N_{1}+S_{2}N_{2}+ \dotsb + S_{k}N_{k}}{N_{1}+N_{2}+\dots +N_{k}} = \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} S_{n} N_{n} 
onumber \ \mathbf{E} &=\dfrac{E_{1}N_{1}+E_{2}N_{2}+ \dotsb + E_{k}N_{k}}{N_{1}+N_{2}+\dots +N_{k}} = \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} E_{n} N_{n} 
onumber \ \mathbf{I} &=\dfrac{I_{1}N_{1}+I_{2}N_{2}+ \dotsb + I_{k}N_{k}}{N_{1}+N_{2}+\dotsb +N_{k}} = \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} I_{n} N_{n} 
onumber \ \mathbf{R} &=\dfrac{R_{1}N_{1}+R_{2}N_{2}+ \dotsb + R_{k}N_{k}}{N_{1}+N_{2}+\dotsb +N_{k}} = \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} R_{n} N_{n} . \end{aligned} \end{equation} The total normalized population of a region (state) or country is given by  egin{equation} \label{eq5} \mathbf{S}+\mathbf{E}+\mathbf{I}+\mathbf{R}=1 \end{equation} The dynamics of SEIR epidemic spreading model that describe the transmission of disease in a population without demography in one region is given by the following system of differential equations :  egin{align} \label{eq6} \dfrac{d\mathbf{S}}{dt}&= - \dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} \left[ \mathbb{S} \mathbb{K}_{\kappa \lambda} ight]_{n} N_{n} \mathbf{I} 
onumber \ \dfrac{d\mathbf{E}}{dt}&=\dfrac{1}{N} \sum_{n=1}^{k} \left[ \mathbb{S} \mathbb{K}_{\kappa \lambda} ight]_{n} N_{n} \mathbf{I} -  rac{1}{T_{inc.}} \mathbf{E} 
onumber \ \dfrac{d \mathbf{I}}{dt}&=  rac{1}{T_{inc.}} \mathbf{E} - rac{1}{T_{inf.}} \mathbf{I} 
onumber \ \dfrac{d \mathbf{R}}{dt}&=  rac{1}{T_{inf.}} \mathbf{I} \end{align} Where $\mathbb{S}=diag(S_{1},\dots,S_{k})$ and $\mathbb{K}_{\kappa \lambda}$ is $(k	imes k)$ mobility infectiousness matrix, with $\mathbf{N}=\mathbf{S}+\mathbf{E}+\mathbf{I}+\mathbf{R}=1$ such that $\mathbf{N}=(N_{1},\dots,N_{k})^T$ and initial condition of dynamics  egin{align}\label{eq7} \mathbf{S_{0}}&=\dfrac{S^0_{1}N_{1} +S^0_{2}N_{2} + \dots S^0_{k}N_{K} }{N} , ~~~` \mathbf{E_{0}}=\dfrac{E^0_{1}N_{1} +E^0_{2}N_{2} + \dots E^0_{k}N_{K} }{N} 
onumber \ \mathbf{I_{0}}&=\dfrac{I^0_{1}N_{1} +I^0_{2}N_{2} + \dots I^0_{k}N_{K} }{N}, ~~~~ \mathbf{R_{0}}=\dfrac{R^0_{1}N_{1} +R^0_{2}N_{2} + \dots R^0_{k}N_{K} }{N} \end{align} Since the $\mathbf{S}$ , $\mathbf{E}$ , $\mathbf{I}$ and $\mathbf{R}$ compartments are scalar by above formula, and the family mobility infectiousness $ \left[ \mathbb{S} \mathbb{K}_{\kappa \lambda} ight]$ is $k	imes k$ matrix, I don't know how to determine the next-generation matrix of this dynamics. Please, I need help! mathematical-modeling epidemics-modeling Share Cite Improve this question Follow edited Aug 15, 2020 at 11:39 YCor 67.5k 5 5 gold badges 203 203 silver badges 301 301 bronze badges asked Aug 11, 2020 at 18:36 Asrat M. B. 9 2 2 bronze badges $\endgroup$ 4 $ egingroup$ If you're using the next-generation matrix to find $R_0$, it may be possible to find a formula $R_0$ using induction. $\endgroup$ Paichu –  Paichu 2020-08-12 18:35:56 +00:00 Commented Aug 12, 2020 at 18:35 $ egingroup$ What do you mean? Your differential equations make sense only if you view $S$, etc. as $k$-component vectors $(S_1,\dots,S_k)$, etc. (in which case everything starts to fit together but the problem stops being one about $\mathbb R^4$ dynamics and becomes one about $\mathbb R^{4k}$ dynamics). In other words, your averaged values alone at the moment $0$ are totally insufficient to determine the full dynamics in a unique way. $\endgroup$ fedja –  fedja 2020-08-13 06:09:41 +00:00 Commented Aug 13, 2020 at 6:09 $ egingroup$ I have edited the question. All variables (S, E, I, R) are positive. $\endgroup$ Asrat M. B. –  Asrat M. B. 2020-08-15 06:07:54 +00:00 Commented Aug 15, 2020 at 6:07 $ egingroup$ As I said: your initial conditions involving the averages only are insufficient for determining the dynamics, so you have to honestly pose and solve the IVP for a system with $4k$ variables. $\endgroup$ fedja –  fedja 2020-08-16 16:20:35 +00:00 Commented Aug 16, 2020 at 16:20 Add a comment  |  0 Sorted b